We recommended the following to management:

Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with unsettled accounts for their immediate settlement. In case of non-settlement of employees who are still connected with the LGU, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;

Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU;

Request for write-off of dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU into Other Receivables account for fair presentation in the Financial Statements in compliance with the Revised Chart of Accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2015-002.

We recommended that management through the GSO to:
account all issued inventories thru the immediate submission of the RSMIs and RSPIs to the Accounting Section for the necessary adjustment in the reported inventory account balances to reflect the correct balance thereof;
ensure the regular preparation and submission of RSMI and RSPI to the Accounting Section to fully account all issuances;
coordinate with the Accounting Section for the periodic reconciliation of their records to early detect any discrepancy and effect corrective measures; and
submit to the office of the Auditor the RPCI and RPCSP as required in Sec. 124 of Chapter 7 of NGAS Volume I and Sec. 4.7.8 of COA Circular No. 2022-004.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

conduct risk assessment; 
identify critical processes and functions; 
determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

