a) The Municipal Accountant to set-up the deficiency on RPT/SET Receivables for CYs 2018 and 2022 and regularly set-up accurate RPT/SET Receivables every accounting period;

b) The Assessors Office to furnish a copy of the assessment roll to the MTO and the latter to submit a list of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year based on the assessment roll to the Accounting Office;

c) The MTO to develop an effective tax collection campaign program to enhance the collection of RPT/SET Receivables specifically in the conduct of an IEC headed by the Municipal Treasurer. This campaign should be conducted by proper officials, with plan set of activities separate from other activities or events in order to attain its main purpose; and

d) With the corroborative effort of the Municipal Treasurer’s Office and Municipal Assessor’s Office, adopt collection remedies as necessary as provided in the above cited provisions.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

a. conduct risk assessment; 

b. identify critical processes and functions; 

c. determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

d. conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

e. formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

f. submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended to Management the following:

1) 	Require all those responsible in the preparation and, approval of trip tickets as well as authorized passenger/s to ensure that driver’s trip ticket is duly and properly accomplished and approved before undertaking the trip. Also, require the preparation of the Driver’s Trip Ticket, Monthly Report of Official Travel, the Fuel Consumption Report for each vehicle/ heavy equipment and Record of Work Done for projects undertaken relative to the subject disbursements and submit the same to the Auditor;

2) 	Requisitions for fuel and other than fuel be supported with RIS and SSMI to properly control and monitor its usage; 

3) 	Municipal Accountant ensure that in the subsequent disbursements for fuel and salaries and wages, the basic documentary requirement as required in COA Circular No. 2012-001 are strictly observed; and.

4) 	Approval of the DTR be made by the approving officer who has a personal knowledge as to the whereabouts and direct supervision of the personnel.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:

1. 	Accountant and the Property Officer to maintain complete property and equipment ledger cards as required under Sec. 43 of NGAS, Volume I and Sec. C3., Chapter V of the Manual on Property Custodianship;

2. 	Inventory Committee to conduct year-end physical inventory on PPE and submit it to the Accounting for reconciliation of balances as a requirement to Sec. 57 of the NGAS Manual, Volume I to ensure correctness and reliability of the PPE account balances;

3. 	Require the Accountant and the General Services Officer to analyze the discrepancy between the balances in the books and per physical count of the PPE Accounts and to make the necessary adjustments in their records to take up the noted differences affecting current year’s transactions; and

4. 	Require the GSO to annually provide a copy of the reconciled RCPPE to the COA, not later than the 31st day of January of ensuing year, showing therein the proper classification of PPE as shown in PPSAS accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

1. 	Reconcile the difference in the balances between the financial statements and the detailed schedule of cash advances;

2. 	Ensure the completeness of prescribed supporting documents for the granting of cash advances in processing claims for payment thereof; 

3. 	Stop granting additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advance granted them have been liquidated; and

4. 	Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances.

